124. Nucleic Acids Res. 2002 Dec 1;30(23):e131. doi: 10.1093/nar/gnf131.

Predicting the success of primer extension genotyping assays using statistical 
modeling.

Yuryev A(1), Huang J, Pohl M, Patch R, Watson F, Bell P, Donaldson M, Phillips 
MS, Boyce-Jacino MT.

Author information:
(1)Orchid Biosciences, Orchid Life Sciences, 303 East College Road, Princeton, 
NJ 08540, USA. ayuryev@orchid.com

Using an empirical panel of more than 20 000 single base primer extension 
(SNP-IT) assays we have developed a set of statistical scores for evaluating and 
rank ordering various parameters of the SNP-IT reaction to facilitate 
high-throughput assay primer design with improved likelihood of success. Each 
score predicts either signal magnitude from primer extension or signal noise 
caused by mispriming of primers and structure of the PCR product. All scores 
have been shown to correlate with the success/failure rate of the SNP-IT 
reaction, based on analysis of assay results. A logistic regression analysis was 
applied to combine all scored parameters into one measure predicting the overall 
success/failure rate of a given SNP marker. Three training sets for different 
types of SNP-IT reaction, each containing about 22 000 SNP markers, were used to 
assign weights to each score and optimize the prediction of the combined 
measure. c-Statistics of 0.69, 0.77 and 0.72 were achieved for three training 
sets. This new statistical prediction can be used to improve primer design for 
the SNP-IT reaction and evaluate the probability of genotyping success for a 
given SNP based on analysis of the surrounding genomic sequence.

